{"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "schema", "document", "Document"], "kwargs": {"metadata": {"producer": "Adobe PDF Library 17.0", "creator": "Adobe InDesign 19.5 (Macintosh)", "creationdate": "2025-06-30T13:23:51+01:00", "moddate": "2025-06-30T13:23:54+01:00", "trapped": "/False", "source": "corpus\\autistic-spectrum-v4.pdf", "total_pages": 47, "page": 25, "page_label": "26"}, "page_content": "26\nSocial stories\nSocial stories present information in a literal and concrete way.  \nThis is beneficial for autistic individuals who sometimes have \nchallenges understanding unwritten social cues and expectations. \nSocial stories can help prepare individuals for new or challenging \nexperiences. Social stories explain what they can expect in a new \nsituation, let them know what options and accommodations are \navailable, and help them feel less worried. They can help individuals \nunderstand what comes next in a series of activities and help \nwith planning and organising. Knowing what to expect can help \nreduce anxiety in unfamiliar situations. Social stories can build \nunderstanding and reduce uncertainty\nThe National Autistic Society website explains that social stories can be used to:\n\u2022 Develop self-care skills (for example how to clean teeth, wash hands, or get \ndressed), social skills (for example sharing, asking for help, saying thank you) and \nacademic abilities", "type": "Document"}}